post_text: The Friends of the Goodrich-Atlas Library will not be holding their traditional fall (September) and Christmas (December) book sale this year due to COVID-19 pandemic restrictions. They will be offering "Grab Bag of Books"for sale inside the ramp lobby of the library. The grab bag of books are $5.00 each and there are several genre's available: mystery/thriller, young adult, historical, romance, and children (age 12 and under) just to list a few. The books are packed into a large reusable shopping bag. There are also several individual books available for purchase in the front lobby of the library and the side ramp lobby. Please bring exact amount of money or checks made payable to: The Friends of the Goodrich-Atlas Library. Please stop by and pick up some books to keep everyone reading at home!

If you requested an absent voter ballot for the August 4 Primary Election, be sure to:
• Vote your ballot (both sides)
• Place your folded ballot into the secrecy sleeve
• Place the secrecy sleeve in the return envelope
• Sign and seal the return envelope
• Return your ballot to your County Clerk’s office by delivering it
yourself, or sending it by mail (public postal, express mail,
parcel post service, or other common carrier).
• If sending via U.S. mail, first class postage is required

post_text: A new program is available for families with children who received free or reduced-cost lunches at school. The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) provides temporary funding for families that need emergency food during the pandemic. There is no need to fill out an application to receive P-EBT benefits. The EBT card will be issued under the name of the oldest student in the household. This card is in addition to the distribution of food taking place at our school district. If you have had a change in your household income and would like to now apply for free or reduced lunch (which will qualify you for P-EBT benefits), applications are available at our food distribution site or by visiting the Food Service Department page on our district website.

post_text: At a special board meeting on Thursday, March 19, the Goodrich Board of Education, at the urging of our Governor, State Senator, and local election coordinators, adopted a resolution withdrawing our bond question from the May 5 ballot, and moving it to August 4, 2020. We wish to thank the leaders of the Citizens for Goodrich Schools, and the greater community for the support you have shown for this much needed bond proposal. We will bring this information before you again, hopefully when life resumes some semblance of normalcy, and ask again for your support to provide a Smarter, Safer, Stronger, Goodrich Area Schools!
text: At a special board meeting on Thursday, March 19, the Goodrich Board of Education, at the urging of our Governor, State Senator, and local election coordinators, adopted a resolution withdrawing our bond question from the May 5 ballot, and moving it to August 4, 2020. We wish to thank the leaders of the Citizens for Goodrich Schools, and the greater community for the support you have shown for this much needed bond proposal. We will bring this information before you again, hopefully when life resumes some semblance of normalcy, and ask again for your support to provide a Smarter, Safer, Stronger, Goodrich Area Schools!

post_text:
According to the Executive Order issued by Governor Whitmer yesterday, all Goodrich Area Schools buildings are closed. The Central and Business Offices will be open in a very limited capacity, in order to continue the essential functions of the district.

Our Food Service Department will continue to provide meals on Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays, from 9:00 to 11:00 a.m., to any child in need, aged 18 and under. This service will continue throughout the shutdown, including over the regularly scheduled spring break week. We will monitor phone messages and respond to emails.

The Governor's "Stay at Home" order is in effect until midnight on Sunday, April 12, which means the mandated school closure is now extended until Monday, April 13. We will continue to communicate with you as we learn more.

Thank you for your patience and understanding. Please follow the CDC guidelines and the "Stay at Home" order from the Governor, to slow the spread of the virus and keep our families safe.

post_text:
In response to the spread of COVID-19 and to meet the needs of our students, Goodrich Area Schools will be distributing meals, for any child in need age 18 and under. Breakfast and lunch items will be available for pick-up Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays, beginning Wednesday, March 18, and running through Friday, April 3. Pick up will be from 9:00 to 11:00 a.m., at Goodrich High School gymnasium entrance #7. These meals are available for all children free of charge.

If you have any questions or concerns regarding meal distribution, please contact Food Service Director, Megan Burny, at 810-591-2236 or 810-591-2250. Be sure to visit our COVID-19 resource page on our district website for updates regarding meal distribution.

post_text: The bond proposal on the May 5 ballot includes construction of a gymnasium at Oaktree Elementary School. The time needed for PE classes forces Oaktree's lunches to start later in the day, resulting in the final lunch period not ending until 1:40 p.m.! A new gymnasium would allow for greater scheduling flexibility as the existing multipurpose room would become a permanent cafeteria during the school day. The new full-size gymnasium will also provide additional practice space for all district athletes.

post_text: Goodrich Community Forum, Wednesday, November 20, 2019, 6:30 p.m. in the Martian Community Room. Please join us for a presentation and discussion for future facility needs, safety improvements, technology upgrades, and potential expansion for the Goodrich Area Schools. With community input/feedback we hope to create a plan that will improve and maintain our facilities and provide a 21st century education, in a safe learning environment, for Goodrich students for years to come.

shared_text:
Martin W. Jennings is with Steve Mitchell and Robin K. Mitchell.
November 13, 2019 at 10:47 AM ·

There are amazing students involved in theatre at Goodrich High School. Yesterday's snow day included the full cast and and crew coming in at 1:00 pm and leaving the theatre last night at 9:45 pm.

Check out the "sneak peek" photos of a few moments from last night's final dress rehearsal of "Ordinary People." Five chances to see the show this weekend: November 13-16 at 7:00 pm and November 17 at 2:30 pm. Call 810-591-2220 to reserve a few tickets! You will see what's so amazing onstage, for sure.
